an battleship Bismarck. Incidents involving the loss of and damage to aircraft carriers, including the sinking of Ark Royal, one of the most famous ships in the early years of World War Two, are also reported. Of major importance are key planning and policy issues. These include the requirements for aircraft carriers, the evolving debate regarding the necessary types of aircraft and attempts to provide sufficient facilities ashore for naval air squadrons.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xAerial operations, British. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xNaval operations, British. 4aMaritime History. 7aHISTORY / Military / World War II.2bisacsh  aAdmiral Sir Andrew Cunningham, Aircraft carriers.  aArk Royal, Bismarck.  aFleet Air Arm.  aGibraltar.  aMalta.  aMediterranean.  aNaval Aviation.  aNorway.  aSecond World War.  aTaranto.  aTrondhein.  aWarships.1 aJones, Ben, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package pre 2013z978311143139040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781315558097423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781315558097/original  a978-3-11-143139-0  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package pre 2013b2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles